Introduction

Stem cell project summary

This Rmarkdown document contains a basic descriptive analysis of the multiple data collected for our 8-day piglet model. The aim at the outset is to identify useful and non-useful data, identify trends and, where possible fit preliminary statistical models. Much of the data wrangling has been hidden for brevity.

Experimental design

Large white piglets (n = 18) aged between 1 and 21 hours of age with body weight between 1.32kg and 2.18kg were used in this project. 7 animals died prior to experimental endpoint and were excluded from the numerical analysis, they have been left in some visualisations where indicated. Approval for this study was obtained from the University of Queensland Animal Experimentation Ethics Committee and was carried out according to the National Health and Medical Research Council guidelines (Australia). All animals used in this project fall under AEC Approval Number: UQCCR/215/18.

Piglets were given a hypoxic-ischaemic insult and allowed to recover. 2 hours later 250,000 stem cells were intravenously administered immedeatly prior to the comencement of hypothermia treatment. Hypothermia was maintained for 24 hours and animals were rewarmed over 10 hours. At the 36 hour time point animals were withdrawn from anaesthesia and recovered to 8 day. Animals were then euthanised and an autopsy was performed.

All investigators were blinded until date of analysis.

We will first explore the data to understand if we are dealing with.

Are our the two HI populations equivalent regarding on physical characteristics?

print(Group_Weight)

Visual inspection of the graphs suggest that the group weights are similar. slightly larger range in the HI+PBS group. NA group reffers to animals that that died prior to treatment, thus suggesting that bodyweight is unrelated in these deaths.

print(Sex_Weight)

There does not appear to be any relationship between birthweights and sex, however it is clear that we have unbalanced groups with regards to sex. Males are more susptible to injury than females. This may influence the end brain outcomes between HI groups.

print(Premature_death_Weight)

2379 and 2368 died with low body weights, it will be worth assessing there liver and brain weights. Low liver weight may be suggestive of IUGR injury in utero. It is unlikely that the other animals died due to weight related factors.

print(Age_start)

It is unclear if death is related to their time at injury. However this graph clearly demonstrates a large difference in range. This is a weakness of our experimental model that could be addressed by beginning the experiment with a c-section.

# With two groups we have unpaired two-sided T test with equal variance
base.multi.t.tests <-
    multi.tests(fun = t.test,
                df = HI_SC_t.test,
                vars = c("Age_at_start", "Brain_weight","Liver_weight","Heart_weight","Body_weight_start"),
                group.var = "Group",
                var.equal = TRUE)

# With two groups we have unpaired two-sided T test with unequal variance
base.multi.welch.t.tests <-
    multi.tests(fun = t.test,
                df = HI_SC_t.test,
                vars = c("Age_at_start", "Brain_weight","Liver_weight","Heart_weight","Body_weight_start"),
                group.var = "Group",
                var.equal = FALSE)

The results of the t-tests demonstrate no difference between groups. We therefore conclude that we have homogenous groups across these factors.

Specifically: Group vs Age_at_start (p = 0.7235424 assuming equal variance: p = 0.7239518 assuming nonequal variance) Group vs Brain_weight (p = 0.3288883 assuming equal variance: p = 0.3342721 assuming nonequal variance) Group vs Liver_weight (p = 0.7104841 assuming equal variance: p = 0.72752 assuming nonequal variance) Group vs Heart_weight (p = 0.3025498 assuming equal variance: p = 0.3559416 assuming nonequal variance) Group vs Body weight (p = 0.9121931 assuming equal variance: p = 0.9123345 assuming nonequal variance)

So we can progress with the assumption that we are dealing with equivalent groups .

Physiology

Next, we must be sure that we have sufficiently injured our HI group compared to control and that we are dealing with homogenous groups regarding injury severity.

Aim

Aim 1: To establish statistical differences between control and HI groups and confirm homogenaity within the HI groups from the physiology data.

Hypothesis

Hypothesis: There will be no difference between HI groups, and significant difference between HI and contol, at the end of HI that returns to normal at 4 hours post insult.

Statistical methods

We will demonstrate no differences between control and HI piglets using a simple hypothesis test and kmeans clustering.

Method 1: T-Test

Method 2: kmeans clustering *The advantage of kmeans clustering is that it takes a multivariate approach and clusters based on euclidian distance within the feature space. This also gives us a method to see how the HI compare to the controls

fviz_cluster(Post_kmeans, df_post, geom = "text", main = "Cluster plot post-HI", ellipse = TRUE, ellipse.type = "norm", show.clust.cent = FALSE, repel = TRUE, xlab = "Principal Component 1 (68.1%)", ylab = "Principal Component 2 (14.5%)")
## Too few points to calculate an ellipse

## Too few points to calculate an ellipse

Clustering via kmeans is suggestive of 2 or three distinct clusters in the pre-HI plot and these are not separable according to their treatment groups. The second plot is highly suggestive of two distinct groups with the clusters totally separable. Plot number 3 suggests that by 4 hours there is no longer a difference between control and HI treated animals.

We can conclude from these data that there is a difference between control and HI treated animals, and no difference between the HI treated groups from the point of view of insult parameters.

Possible questions: What is Principal components analysis? It is the technique used to reduce the dimensionality of a dataset.

What are the steps to obtaining the principal components? 1. Take the whole dataset consisting of d+1 dimensions and ignore the labels such that our new dataset becomes d dimensional. 2. Compute the mean for every dimension of the whole dataset. 3. Compute the covariance matrix of the whole dataset. 4. Compute eigenvectors and the corresponding eigenvalues. 5. Sort the eigenvectors by decreasing eigenvalues and choose k eigenvectors with the largest eigenvalues to form a d k dimensional matrix W. 6. Use this d k eigenvector matrix to transform the samples onto the new subspace.

NeuN to label neurons FJC to label degenerating neurons Caspase 3 to label apoptotic cells GFAP to label astrocytes CD34 to quantify angiogenesis IBA to quantify immune upregulation.
